hat mean life is negative entropy? <a href=\"http://www.masterorganicchemistry.com/2010/10/28/the-marriage-may-be-bad-but-the-divorce-still-costs-money/\" rel=\"nofollow\">masterorganicchemistry.com/2010/10/28/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8f390793b0da7cf39ecdb5837e0ce9c5?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21120,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21120/amphibio","reputation":150,"display_name":"Amphibio"},"score":0,"post_id":44178,"edited":false,"creation_date":1457656574,"comment_id":76734,"body":"My guess would be that, as complex organisms, we make more complex molecules than we break ---&gt; net exothermic ---&gt; entropy"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1457653414,"creation_date":1457652443,"body":"<p><strong>Metabolism ≈ Anabolism + catabolism<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metabolism\" rel=\"nofollow\">Metabolism<\/a> is the set of all chemical reactions happening inside a living body. These reactions can either breaks down big molecules and build up big molecules. The set of reactions the breaks down big molecules is called <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catabolism\" rel=\"nofollow\">catabolism<\/a>. The set of reactions that build up big molecules is called <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anabolism\" rel=\"nofollow\">anabolism<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Energy<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Generally speaking, anabolism cost energy and catabolism yield energy. The molecule that is directly used to transfer this energy is <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenosine_triphosphate\" rel=\"nofollow\">Adenosine triphosphate (ATP)<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Any energy transfer is coupled with some loss of energy from the system (see <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Energy_conversion_efficiency\" rel=\"nofollow\">Energy conversion efficiency<\/a>).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Entropy<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>For any chemical reactions, there is always an overall increase of entropy. As a consequence, a living organism increases the entropy in its surrounding. In other words, it breaks more than it builds.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Your question<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>does life make or break?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Life does both! But on average, it mainly breaks things up (just like any other chemical reaction).<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Want to learn more?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>The concepts of energy and entropy are studied in physics and chemistry but not so much in biology. I cannot really give you a good source of information.<\/p>\n\n<p>Khan Academy offers a very good introductory course on metabolism (<a href=\"https://www.khanacademy.org/test-prep/mcat/biomolecules/overview-metabolism/v/overview-of-metabolism-anabolism-and-catabolism\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>), you should have a look!<\/p>\n","answer_id":44178,"question_id":44175,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1457653414}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44175/does-life-make-or-break","last_activity_date":1457653414,"creation_date":1457650452,"answer_count":1,"title":"does life make or break?","body":"<p>Ok, this question seems like it may be impossible to answer, but would be interesting to see if anyone has an idea.<\/p>\n\n<p>Throughout the course of a human life, do we make more molecular bonds than we break, or vice versa?<\/p>\n","question_id":44175,"tags":["molecular-biology","digestive-system","systems-biology","biosynthesis"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":44178,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/YMlKc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3776,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3776/satwik-pasani","reputation":2491,"display_name":"Satwik Pasani","accept_rate":68},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/f0PGT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3615,"link":"http://