pike","accept_rate":70},"score":2,"post_id":36233,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1437665726,"comment_id":60252,"body":"Do you have anything to add? The sum of this seems to be it is subjective. If that is correct, then yes I am satisfied."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/12086f42e1380495f6b35592ce60b0e4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11652,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11652/stan-shunpike","reputation":819,"display_name":"Stan Shunpike","accept_rate":70},"score":2,"post_id":36233,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1437667036,"comment_id":60255,"body":"I wrote this mainly so that, in case the link breaks, the info is available."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":36233,"edited":false,"creation_date":1437690402,"comment_id":60274,"body":"I can add something to question two, which seems unanswered. Let me know if you are interested."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/12086f42e1380495f6b35592ce60b0e4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11652,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11652/stan-shunpike","reputation":819,"display_name":"Stan Shunpike","accept_rate":70},"score":1,"post_id":36233,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1437708194,"comment_id":60289,"body":"Yes, that will be great. I am going to accept your other answers too by the way. I just have had to mull them over a bit. Thanks for your efforts :)"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1437386037,"creation_date":1437386037,"body":"<p>An Initial clarification of what \"loss of sensation\" means: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The history in the patient with \u201cnumbness\u201d is extremely important. First of all, as with most neurologic complaints, you must determine what the patient means by \u201cnumbness.\u201d Some patients are describing loss of sensitivity (anesthesia or hypesthesia) or distorted sensations (paresthesia), which is often described as tingling. Actual loss of sensitivity is more likely to represent true damage to sensory pathways in the nervous system, while paresthesia has a much broader differential. Dysesthesia, that is the perception of an unpleasant (often burning) sensation or allodynia (the perception of innocuous stimuli as being painful) may result from damage to the nervous system or, more commonly, be the manifestation of an underlying painful condition.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Some properties of numbness <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The pattern of numbness may help define its origin. Numbness confined to a specific nerve or nerve root distribution (see the maps of dermatomes and peripheral nerve sensory innervation) lead to consideration of peripheral nerve or nerve root damage. Loss of sensation on one side of the body is more likely to result from central nervous system damage and if the sensory loss also involves the same side of the face, you can be sure that the cause is located above the level of the pons.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>When there is a clear sensory level (a line on the body, below which sensations are lost), a spinal cord lesion must be suspected. Loss of sensation over the upper limbs or upper part of the trunk bilaterally, with preservation over the lower limbs and buttocks, suggests an expanding intraspinal mass. This so-called \u201csacral sparing\u201d is seen with intraspinal tumors or syrinxes. Numbness over one side of the face, while being a relatively common presentation of psychiatric disease, can also be caused by damage to the lateral part of the brain stem, or upper spinal cord (spinal tract of the trigeminal). Lateral brain stem damage can also produce a picture of sensory decrease on one side of the head and on the opposite side of the body.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>But the article concludes <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>In summary, the evaluation of numbness can be quite frustrating due to its subjective nature. <\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>So it is in essence a term that <em>can<\/em> have specific meanings uncertain contexts, but one must be careful to clarify exactly how the term is being used since there isn't one single meaning. <\/p>\n\n<p>This is all from this link here \n<a href=\"https://www.dartmouth.edu/~dons/part_2/chapter_13.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.dartmouth.edu/~dons/part_2/chapter_13.html<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":36233,"question_id":36213,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/12086f42e1380495f6b35592ce60b0e4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11652,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11652/stan-shunpike","reputation":819,"display_name":"Stan Shunpike","accept_rate":70},"score":0,"post_id":36518,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438372001,"comment_id":60771,"body":"This is much more what I had in mind. To be honest, I thought this was what numbness <i>was<\/i> before getting into the use of the term."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1438354444,"creation_date":1438353849,"body":"<p>The definition of numbness has been answered by yourself, and I will focus on the second part of the question.<\/p>\n\n<p>In terms of the underlying physiological mechanism behind numbness I think it's good to narrow the question down and focus on <strong>local anesthetics<\/strong>, which numb a local area of the body for minor surgical procedures. Cocaine and related compounds have been shown to block not only pain, but also warmth, cold and touch perception, as well as blocking motor function. Cocain and related compounds are basically voltage-gated Na<sup>+<\/sup> channel blockers, but also block K<sup>+<\/sup> channels to some extent. Their affinity to various different channels differs, explaining the differential effects. E.g., pain is blocked more effectively than motor functions <a href=\"http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/89/1/52.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Scholz, 2002)<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>We all know the feeling of numbness when our limbs are asleep due to restriction of blood flow. Likely all neural activity is blocked here too, as the cutting off of oxygen affects all neurons.<\/p>\n\n<p>Given the broad range of effects of local anesthetics and restriction of blood flow, I would tentatively conclude that numbness can be interpreted as a <em>reduction of sensitivity of all the senses<\/em>.  <\/p>\n\n<p><sup><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://bja.oxfordjournals.org/content/89/1/52.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">Scholz, <em>Br J Anaesth<\/em> (2002); <strong>89<\/strong>; 52-61<\/a><\/sup><\/p>\n","answer_id":36518,"question_id":36213,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1438354444}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/36213/is-numbness-the-absence-of-one-or-all-touch-sensations","last_activity_date":1457643286,"creation_date":1437329552,"answer_count":2,"title":"Is numbness the absence of one or all touch sensations?","body":"<p>I am studying the effects of tetrodotoxin and its symptoms when consumed. Numbness is one of the first sensations reported. <\/p>\n\n<p>But I googled numbness and I couldn't find information about whether this means all touch sensations (e.g. thermal, mechano, etc) have to be absent for numbness or just one specific kind. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>My Question:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Define numbness<\/li>\n<li>Explain whether numbness is the absence of one or more than one or all touch sensations. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","question_id":36213,"tags":["neuroscience","homework","neurophysiology","touch"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":36518,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":97,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1457643286},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/D2RQc.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15358,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15358/mhooper03","reputation":33,"display_name":"MHooper03"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1457642112,"creation_date":1457642112,"body":"<p><strong>Short answer<\/strong><br>\nTouch receptors become unresponsive after continuous stimulation, a process called neural adaptation. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Background<\/strong><br>\nThere are various touch receptors in the skin (Fig. 1). One of them is the <a href=\"https://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/imagepages/9703.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>hair follicle receptor<\/strong><\/a>. These receptors form sensory nerve fibers that wrap around each hair bulb. Bending the hair stimulates the nerve endings.<\/p>\n\n<p>All the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Afferent_nerve_fiber\" rel=\"nofollow\">afferent fibers<\/a> of the skin receptors in the skin show <strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_adaptation\" rel=\"nofollow\">neural adaptation<\/a><\/strong>. A rough classification of the various skin receptors is grouping them in <strong>rapidly<\/strong> and <strong>slowly adapting<\/strong> fibers.<\/p>\n\n<p>Rapidly adapting fibers respond mainly to <strong>pressure changes<\/strong>. Typical examples are the Pacinian and Meissner's corpuscles, but also the hair follicle receptor.<\/p>\n\n<p>Fig. 1. shows a <strong>static stimulation<\/strong> of the various receptors. Upon initial stimulation, the hair follicle receptor (Fig. 1a) vigorously fires action potentials. Because the hair follicle receptor rapidly adapts, however, it soon stops responding when the hair is continuously, statically bent in that same direction. Once the stimulus is removed it fires another volley of action potentials because the hair moves again.<\/p>\n\n<p>In other words, the hair follicle receptor responds to strokes, stretch and skin vibrations, as it is a novelty detector; it detects <strong>change<\/strong>, just like Pacinian and Meissner's corpuscles do (Fig. 1b,c). This opposed to Merkel cells and Ruffini endings (Fig.1d,e) - these receptors are designed to continuously fire action potentials upon a static pressure stimulus (Fig. 1), although even these receptors eventually give up and become unresponsive.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/beyQC.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/beyQC.jpg\" alt=\"skin receptors\"><\/a><br>\n<sup>Fig. 1. The skin receptors and neural adaptation. source: <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v12/n3/fig_tab/nrn2993_F1.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Delmas <em>et al<\/em>., (2011)<\/a><\/sup>  <\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/nrn/journal/v12/n3/fig_tab/nrn2993_F1.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Delmas <em>et al<\/em>., <em>Nature Rev Neurosci<\/em> (2011); <strong>12<\/strong>: 139-15<\/a><\/sub>     <\/p>\n","answer_id":44169,"question_id":44167,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44167/why-do-we-only-initially-feel-the-bending-of-a-hair","last_activity_date":1457642425,"creation_date":1457639015,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do we only initially feel the bending of a hair?","body":"<p>In my neurobiology class, my professor prompted us to take the tip of our pencil and fold or push down a single strand of hair on our arm or leg in the opposite direction that it grows in. He then commented on how we are able to detect the initial stimulus, but how after a while we no longer feel the hair being bent. <\/p>\n\n<p>My question is thus, why does this occur? Why would we suddenly no longer be able to feel the stimulus of the hair being forced back?<\/p>\n","question_id":44167,"tags":["neurophysiology","touch"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":44169,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1457642425},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-CiM5t4hXuiY/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAM8/eYb-54L3ZgE/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":22305,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22305/daniel-bryden-johnson","reputation":31,"display_name":"Daniel Bryden Johnson"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kIqWF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19099,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19099/another-homo-sapien","reputation":1004,"display_name":"another 'Homo sapien'"},"score":0,"post_id":44142,"edited":false,"creation_date":1457605763,"comment_id":76688,"body":"I remember another method. Isolate the plasmid and use restriction enzymes specific to ampR (Pvu I &