zwnj;&#8203;ize<\/a>."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"post_id":44121,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9f137c8bccd23ae845550c5e95c1e31b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4821,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4821/rodrigo","reputation":478,"display_name":"Rodrigo"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1457571015,"comment_id":76662,"body":"@Rodrigo However, the rate at which neutral mutation fix is the same. The reason is that the probability of a neutral mutation to fix is $\\frac{1}{2N}$. There are $2N\\mu$ new mutations entering the population each generation and therefore the rate of fixation of neutral mutations is $\\frac{1}{2N} \\cdot 2N\\mu = \\mu$. This classic result is essential for phylogenetic reconstruction typically as we can infer time of divergence from the rate of neutral divergence without knowing anything about $N$."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44121/how-much-of-the-genetic-differences-between-humans-and-chimpanzees-are-due-to-ge","last_activity_date":1457541890,"creation_date":1457540895,"answer_count":0,"title":"How much of the genetic differences between humans and chimpanzees are due to genetic drift?","body":"<p>Both natural selection and genetic drift play a part in changing our DNA over time. Are there trustworthy estimates how much of the differences over the whole genome between us and chimpanzees are due to genetic drift and how much is due to natural selection?<\/p>\n","question_id":44121,"tags":["evolution"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":39,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1457541890},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user22432"},"closed_date":1457541500,"comments":[{"owner":{"prof