d and Marrow Transplantation (EBMT). The best overall survival (OS) from the time of transplantation was found in F right arrow F (median 41 months) with no significant difference between other groups (median 25 months in M right arrow M, 18 months in F right arrow M, 19 months in M right arrow F) despite a significantly higher nonrelapse mortality in F right arrow M. This was due to a significantly lower relapse rate (REL) in F right arrow M compared to all other groups. Before 1994, OS was poorer in F right arrow M than in M right arrow M, which improved to similarity from 1994 onwards (median 29 months in M right arrow M and 25 months in F right arrow M). The reduced REL contributed to this improvement in F right arrow M indicting a sex-specific graft vs myeloma effect. <strong>Therefore, a female donor is as good as a male one for male patients, while for female patients gender disparity is a negative factor for outcome.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>from: <a href=\"https://www.broadinstitute.org/news/1386\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.broadinstitute.org/news/1386<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>\"It's been clear for some time that bone marrow transplants involving a female donor and a male patient pose a higher risk of GVHD,\" said Bradner. \"This \u2018sex mismatch' arises from genes that are carried on the male-specific Y chromosome and are therefore present in males but not in females...\"<\/p>\n","answer_id":43923,"question_id":43894,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1457531175}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43894/is-a-bone-marrow-transplant-limited-by-sex","last_activity_date":1457531175,"creation_date":1456985303,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is a bone marrow transplant limited by sex?","body":"<p>Can a female patient get transplanted with bone marrow of a male donor and vice versa?<\/p>\n","question_id":43894,"tags":["human-biology","genetics","molecular-biology","zoology","medicine"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":68,"up_vote_c