When those networks are trained, the 'weights', which are analog to synaptic strength, of all neurons of one layer have an equivalent local topology, and thus can be mapped between the neurons, and finally unified. This way, only one 'weight' is trained for all equivalent synapses on all neurons of an layer.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is there any biological mechanism found that may sport this feature? My guess would be that the vision cortex is partly organised by self structuring not depending on neural activation to achieve low level vision processing. Otherwise, all neurons in one 'layer' would need a way to exchange information to synchronize their synaptic structure. <\/p>\n\n<p>However, I guess that the human brain would have some mechanism of this kind, as it would provide for example the ability to learn the detection of certain visual patterns or events independent of their retinal position, without learning the detection individually for every image location. <\/p>\n\n<p>Is any such mechanism known or how could it work?<\/p>\n","question_id":36412,"tags":["neuroscience","brain","visual-system"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":153,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/F278S.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22237,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22237/nemexia","reputation":116,"display_name":"Nemexia"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/F278S.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":22237,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/22237/nemexia","reputation":116,"display_name":"Nemexia"},"score":0,"post_id":44088,"edited":false,"creation_date":1457454234,"comment_id":76587,"body":"Thanks for answer, helped alot @March Ho"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1457448986,"creation_date":1457448986,"body":"<p>The protein involved in \"pushing\" the tRNA and mRNA is the elongation factor <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/EF-G\" rel=\"nofollow\">EF-G<\/a>. The protein involved in \"transporting\" the tRNA is the elongation factor <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EF-Tu\" rel=\"nofollow\">EF-Tu<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>Quoted from the Wikipedia articles:<\/p>\n\n<p>EF-G:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>When it binds to the ribosome A-site, EF-G causes the tRNA previously occupying that site to occupy an intermediate A/P position (bound to the A site of the small ribosomal subunit and to the P site of the large subunit), and the tRNA in the P site is shifted to a P/E hybrid state. EF-G hydrolysis of GTP causes a conformation change that forces the A/P tRNA to fully occupy the P site, the P/E tRNA to fully occupy the E site (and exit the ribosome complex), and the mRNA to shift three nucleotides down relative to the ribosome due to its association with these tRNA molecules. The GDP-bound EF-G molecule then dissociates from the complex, leaving another free A-site where the elongation cycle can start again<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>EF-Tu:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The tRNA anticodon domain associates with the mRNA codon domain in the ribosomal A site. If the codon-anticodon pairing is correct, EF-Tu hydrolyzes guanosine triphosphate (GTP) into guanosine diphosphate (GDP) and inorganic phosphate. This creates a conformational change in EF-Tu that causes EF-Tu to dissociate from the tRNA of the ternary complex (and therefore leave the ribosome). The aminoacyl-tRNA then fully enters the A site, where its amino acid is brought near the P site's polypeptide and the ribosome catalyzes the covalent transfer of the polypeptide onto the amino acid . The tRNA on the P site (without peptide) moves to the E site and is then released.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":44088,"question_id":44087,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/44087/identification-of-proteins-in-this-animation-of-a-ribosome-translating-mrna","last_activity_date":1457489537,"creation_date":1457448551,"answer_count":1,"title":"Identification of proteins in this animation of a ribosome translating mRNA","body":"<p><img src=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/94/Protein_translation.gif\" alt=\"\"><\/p>\n\n<p>This gif is from <a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Translation_(biology)\" rel=\"nofollow\">this page<\/a>\nAfter each aminoacyl-tRNA enters the ribosome, one blue thing comes and pushes the whole tRNAs whats that? I couldn't find it anywhere.(maybe some elongation factor?)\nAlso it seems that some thing is transporting the tRNA itself (maybe aminoacyl tRNA synthetase?)<\/p>\n","question_id":44087,"tags":["translation","ribosome"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":44088,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":24,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1457489537},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b5f13f68dc4b7413ed4a6e12276ebc97?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":21720,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21720/olah-andrei","reputation":1,"display_name":"Olah Andrei"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TSuGp.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19521/jordi-zambrino","reputation":1024,"display_name":"Jordi Zambrino","accept_rate":83},"score":1,"post_id":43093,"edited":false,"creation_date":1454849944,"comment_id":74335,"body":"read into <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dephosphorylation\" rel=\"nofollow\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dephosphorylation<\/a> and <a href=\"https://www.boundless.com/biology/textbooks/boundless-biology-textbook/metabolism-6/atp-adenosine-trip