those found\n  in R1.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>This statement seems incorrect.<\/p>\n\n<p>Paired-end reads comes from opposite ends of a fragment (you could learn the reason it happens from Illumina's <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=womKfikWlxM\" rel=\"nofollow\">video<\/a>). If insert size is 150bp, read length usually is ~60bp as quality score after 60th bp is unacceptably low. In this case, R1 length is ~60bp, and it is 5'3', R2 length is ~60bp, and it is 3'5'. When a number of reads are enough to cover the gap, they form a contig.<\/p>\n\n<p>Here's an illustration from Illumina's <a href=\"http://www.illumina.com/technology/next-generation-sequencing/paired-end-sequencing_assay.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">website<\/a>:\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/4FlkV.gif\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/4FlkV.gif\" alt=\"From Illumina&#39;s website\"><\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":44098,"question_id":38646,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1457467798}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/38646/what-do-illumina-hiseq-miseq-paired-end-reads-look-like","last_activity_date":1457467798,"creation_date":1441818848,"answer_count":2,"title":"What do Illumina HiSeq/MiSeq paired end reads look like?","body":"<p>My understanding is that paired end reads from the Illumina HiSeq/MiSeq platforms looks something like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>R1:\n    AAAAAACCCCCC\nR2:\n    GGGGGGTTTTTT\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Where the reads found in R2 are the reverse complement of those found in R1. This does not appear to be the case however, for my sequencing data. If it helps I have a read pair from one of my MiSeq runs below.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>R1:\n@M01814:86:000000000-A6MU9:1:1101:15397:1339 1:N:0:2\nTACTCGCACCTATCCGGCACAGCAACACCATCTGGGGCTGAATCGCAATAGCATCTCTCACTTCCTCCATATCAGATTGCTCAAGGCAAGCACTACGCTGCAGTGCCCTCCACTCCCAATTCCCTGATGCTGGTCGTAACTTGCCACACCA\n+\n&gt;&gt;AA?BBBBBFFGGG2EEEGFBGHHHGA2FGHBGHF2EE?GHGHHFFEEHDGHEFGF5FEEFBGHGBCB5FHHH5F553@434FF31G11??233B